Comment:
For those of you who have seen Ocean's 8 the picture, try to recall the last scene. Sandra sits down on a wooden bench which faces a wall of multiple engraved tombs. As she pours her beverage into a martini glass, pay close attention to the tombstone to her lowest bottom right.

Engraved into the granite facing appear the words 'Helga M. Meyer' 1992 ‚Äì 2010 as the date of birth and death of the deceased. Sandra's biological mother sadly passed on April 4, 2000--her name was as it appears on the tombstone in the movie -- Helga M. Meyer.

The last words of dialog spoken as Sandy gazes directly into the camera in this final scene right before it fades to black and the end credits begin roll are-- "you would've loved it."

This is no coincidence. The final scene is cleverly crafted as a sentimental homage to her deceased mother who didn't get to see her daughter's best work, and who was by death denied the opportunity to witness her beloved daughter receive an Academy Award.

Although Helga may not be with you in the physical form Sandra, she will always be with you in spirit and is aware of what a remarkable woman you've become artistically-- including the adoptions of two beautiful children in desperate need of someone in this cruel world to want them, to need them, to love them.

Well done Sandra... Well done.

The MET was a good location but the "only" good location. I missed the cryptic conversations between Danny and Rusty, there unique chemistry was pure cinema. You felt a genuine friendship. There was so much more 8 could do... Better location scouting, interesting dialogue, and more focus on character development. I need to emphasize with the characters not just wacht a heist unfold. This movie needed a better "want"( a reason to heist in the first place). It was always about the style and the flair and not the heist itself. Very disappointed in this cash grab.. Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
I'm definitely not one to yell "no way" every time a story takes a few liberties to stretch into the implausible.  But Oceans 8 starts taking on water from the get-go, starting with the hard-to-miss runway-worthy makeup job Bullock sports before the parole board. From there, every attempt to patch the film's breached hull only hastens her demise.  The movie capsized early enough in the film that we should have known to walk out and reclaim our evening when a key vehicle of the con (involving a special 3D printer) is so preposterous that it is insulting.  They'd have been better off rubbing a genie out of a bottle and getting their three wishes.  We sat there hoping at least the action would build pace and save this wretched thing, but it never did.  It was tiresome in every regard and scoff-worthy at every turn.

In the car, on the way home, as my wife and I lamented the loss of two hours of a Tuesday summer night, I found myself explaining to her where the term "jumping the shark" came from.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
First of all, this series didn't need to exist past the first film. They all followed the same exact formula and weren't very interesting to watch after the first. Basically boils down to, two characters decide to pull a radical heist, they have to recruit talent for each scenario in the form of a montage, they train for the heist montage, they perform the heist montage, it appears as though they fail the heist to add artificial stakes, they reveal information to the audience the writers intentionally kept from them so they can pull off an unexpected twist to show how they were successful. BOOM! Ocean's movie. Predictable and doesn't carry an entire franchise. Even worse is how the film's design is to show you every plan for the heist except the most important one that will guarantee their success. It's a cheap plot twist that relies on withholding information rather than misdirection and smart writing.

Secondly, while I'm not against an all female cast, this one in particular makes no sense. There is literally no reason for their team to be made up of entirely women especially during the recruitment process because pulling off a large scale heist that requires precision timing and experts in their respective roles means you hire the right person for the job because of their skill, not their gender. I'm all for equality but that means assimilation not segregation. You want to promote female diversity in film? Cast more women in your project along side the males. Otherwise this is forced feminism catering to one audience over the other.

It's the same reason why I think BET is a stupid channel. Having an all black channel and an all black awards show promotes segregation. Why would we come this far just to go backwards? We keep talking about equality but no one actually wants to put forth the effort in assimilation. They all want their own things. So we have the women's channel, black channel, Latino channel, Korean channel. We can't keep creating little entertainment pockets that cater to one audience. That is literally the exact opposite of equality.

Rebecca Buck - Tank Girl

like the ghostbusters... while saying it is still in the same universe "in the 80s 4 scientists" then making all the new female characters basically just like the original characters in terms of backgrounds, spengler..... but not related to egon? dana... as some crazy scientist woman with an accent.. using the original actors but not as there original characters and killing one off (likely because it was obvious murray wanted nothing to do with anymore of the movies which is why he alone halted the production of a ghostbusters 3 almost his whole life) it was just a mess of pointlessness with callbacks and constant saturday night live adlibbing... I know the original actors all worked on SNL but the comedy the did on there was far from the dry comedy used in the original ghostbusters.

Anyway i've ranted on WAY too long for a comment on a simple sequel movie and I feel like a bit of a cun.t for that but hey maybe many feel the same way, from the likes to dislikes i'm guessing so, and I doubt all of them are men as plenty of women see how bad some of these movies are becoming to it isn't a sex thing...... I guess it's a movie lovers thing.

Comment:
This film has a stink to it that most people can't explain so they immediately jump on the most basic interpretation, which you see in the form of previous comments, in a nutshell "this film is sexist towards men", "they are ruining the original", and so on. 
In actuality, I believe there is a little more to it and if you'll follow me, I'd like to try explain why the FILM is actually WAY more sexist.

First, I'd like to point out that while the male version of first Ocean's film had the guys rob a casino, the female version appears to be stealing a necklace. Because I guess they figure woman like shiny things, so lets have them steal jewelry. Not patronizing at all...
Next, why is this an Ocean's film to begin with? Why not just make a simple Heist movie with women and call it something else? Answer: They wanted to the namebrand and the controversy. 
The makers of this film don't give a shit about equal representation. They want a quick buck by piggybacking off an established franchise and the free publicity from the outrage.
Fools on both side can't see that they are being used to promote this film. Same thing happened with Ghostbusters. You're all being played.

These things never cease to annoy simply because they are so contrived.
People are told clearly and firmly that this is a cheap attempt fueled by a cynical lust for easy money and a skewed and forced sense of social justice.

And because the intent was never pure and honest to begin with, neither will the movie feel that way. It won't feel like art, but like a cheap and forced attempt for our money and attention. It deserves all our disdain and more and I hope that this unreasonable bs could finally stop.

Look if you wake up from a dream that involved all women or had an epiphany that just screamed "women" go for it and create your original art for the world to enjoy. But don't make some hacky contrived bs then call us misogynistic for not taking the bait. What a bad time we live in, where on all sides and ideologies, passion comes firmly before any consideration for rationality and truth.

Edit:
And what a bad time when you can make yourself feel like a "good man or good woman", by denying yourself the natural wisdom and rationality that talks against the forced and contrived ways of thought. Jesus, culture never moves freely.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment: The only comparison I can think of that works between this and Ghostbusters (2016) is simply the all-female angle.  But if you think harder about it, this isn't nearly as cynical a cash-grab.  Oh sure, it's trying to use the Ocean's name for brand-recognition, but (1) Ocean's has never been as beloved a cultural phenomenon as Ghostbusters to begin with, so that makes this easier to accept, and (2) Ocean's doesn't hinge on balancing two very different genres like Ghostbusters does with horror and comedy (and which the 2016 film failed spectacularly at).  Ocean's have always just been heist movies, and their most distinct quality is that they're way bigger team-ups than most heist movies are (though The Sting would beg to differ, even if that's more of a con movie than a heist movie XD).  So as long as it works as a heist movie, this'll be just fine.  This isn't some "betrayal" of the series, guys, and Ghostbusters didn't strictly fail because the team was all-female.  It failed because Sony had no bucking clue how to make a Ghostbusters movie and did the most boring and predictable things they could with the cast they had.  So give this one a chance, it already looks a million times more interesting than Ghostbusters 2016 ever did.

Comment:
The reason a lot of people are mocking this movie isn't that it has a female cast. Plenty of movies have had female casts, and no one gave a shit. The problem with this movie (and Ghostbusters 2016) is that it feels like the writers have tried to shoehorn women into roles that just make more sense for men. 
Men tend to be more reckless, they tend to be more interested in tinkering with things (like vaults and security systems), and they tend to be greedier, as well. Thus, they make more sense as thieves. Not that you could never write a plausible female thief, but a group of 8 of them? Come on.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
I'm really worried about this film not being any good. Just based on the trailer, it seems like it doesn't have the same style, themes, or mood that the trilogy did, which is why I think it looks like it really shouldn't be an Oceans movie. It looks as if it would be absolutely great as a standalone film in its own universe, just not as a part of the Oceans series.

I really really really want it to be well made, as I want all the films under the Oceans series name to be good, but the fact that Danny is dead is a huge turn off for me. The chemistry that the original cast had was absolutely perfect for those films and the mood they had. I'm curious to see if the cast of this one can keep up with that. There's no doubt that they've got a lot of great A-list actors in it, but just because they're great actors doesn't mean they're a great fit for the film, and I would really like to see them portray their roles well.

All in all, I'm not all that excited about an Oceans film without George Clooney/Danny Ocean as the main character, but I'll be willing to give it a watch after it's left the theater. If I hear that it's really good when it comes out, I'll be a lot more inclined to see it in the Cinema. Here's to hoping that they execute this film well, and that it doesn't become another disappointing attempt at a series revival.

This is so sad. Women have had tons of awesome female characters, in action, drama, comedy, etc. All these reboots-with-women movies just give the impression to people that women can't do cool things without nabbing a story from a different, male-led, franchise, while there've been plenty of good examples of this stretching back (probably far, far more, but this is purely my limited movie watching experience) to at least Alien in 1979. Plenty of recent examples from English-language to foreign. just in the last few years. People seem extra whiny about action stars which bugs me because, yeah they're movies, but I have to point out that that just statistically, it's more likely for a guy to be in those sorts of roles, both in wanting to do action movies as actors, and as characters, where men are more likely to be involved in this sort of thing in real life, so here's some strong, female-led/co-led films right off the top of my head, both in English and abroad, examples of non-pandering, believable female character who aren't just "women being men." Truth is that women are different to men, but no less brave, daring, and intelligent. More movies should acknowledge this difference, which doesn't prevent them from being badass. Here's some off the top of my head (dozens I'm doubtless missing, just from  last few years, but I''m not  going  to make this post longer than it is already going to be.

Comment: I really like Sandra Bullock, so it's hard to take a shit on the idea of this movie. However, "Ocean's 8?" So you had to make an all female one because the Ocean's Eleven (the only one that matters) didn't have females in it? Why not just take a similar cast and make an original idea? For the people that say, "Well, I don't think this has anything to do with the 'Ocean's' movies." Really? It's in the title, with a different number, and it's based on the same exact concept: a group of professional thieves come together to rip off something super valuable. And to the people who say, "you just don't want women to do movies like these." Untrue, in fact most fans loved Charlize Theron from The Italian Job for example. Her character fit perfectly in that story. There's plenty of movies out there with male leads that we(men) take a huge shit on because it sucks; the idea sucks, the direction sucks, the cast sucks. Just getting tired of Hollywood looking for "woman power" movies. We (men) loved Sigourney Weaver of Alien(s), Linda Hamilton of The Terminator series, Carrie Anne Moss of The Matrix, Uma Thurman of Kill Bill, etc. So it's not about hating on women, it's about Hollywood basically remaking old greats but recasting with all females for the purpose of pushing feminism. It's supposed to be about art, not political/social agendas. I'll give it a chance, because again, Sandra Bullock is a fantastic actress. But come on! Come up with something freaking original!

In contrast to:

Note that I'm taking about major blockbusters with a MAJORITY female cast (not just one female character solely there to break up the sausage fest and mostly get killed or kidnapped to give wonder bread protagonist something to angst and grit his teeth over) that have major studio backing, star power, and decent marketing. Comment: You know, if this sequel/spin-off wasn't centered around Danny Ocean's sister and her female heist team but some long lost son of his and all his male buddies, I'm sure there would be people saying "this is gonna suck, why did they have to do this, etc" but not once would the gender of the cast be an issue anyone would bring up as a reason not to watch it/why it would suck. If you're not a fan of multiple sequels or spin-offs or you just think it was unnecessary to revisit this universe, that's totally valid but if it's purely for the reason that this main cast is female and you would otherwise enjoy it if it wasn't, maybe you have some re-evaluating to do. Hollywood revisits cinematic universes all the time to cash in on the popularity of a franchise. Multiple/belated sequels and spin-offs are not a new thing. If you think such films are of a lesser cinematic quality or just not your thing, that's understandable but the gender of the cast doesn't lessen the cinematic value, however.

Compare the strong female lead in Star Wars Rogue One who kicks butt without having to prove anything, against the Rey character of the Force Awakens shaking away Finn‚Äôs hand when he tries to pull her to safety, Captain Phantasma character written as male and changed to female, Andy Serkis talking about Snoke‚Äôs fear of a feminine power. When I write a story, the female characters kick ass because that‚Äôs what appeals to me and that is what my male characters find attractive, like Lagertha in Vikings- I don‚Äôt like the useless, pretty princess, I like the shield maiden who can hold her own. Comment:
Resistance¬†fighters led by General¬†Leia Organa¬†evacuate their base when a¬†First Orderfleet arrives. Following an effective but costly counterattack led by¬†Poe Dameron, the Resistance vessels jump into hyperspace to escape, but the First Order follows using a tracking device.¬†Kylo Ren, Leia's son, destroys the Resistance support fighters, but hesitates to fire at the lead Resistance ship after sensing his mother's presence.¬†TIE fightersdestroy the bridge of the ship, killing several Resistance leaders and incapacitating Leia, leaving¬†Vice Admiral Holdo¬†in command. Disapproving of Holdo's passive strategy, Poe,¬†Finn,¬†BB-8, and mechanic¬†Rose Tico¬†embark on a secret plan to disable the tracking device.

Meanwhile,¬†Rey¬†has arrived on remote¬†Ahch-To¬†with¬†Chewbacca¬†and¬†R2-D2¬†aboard the¬†Millennium Falcon¬†to recruit¬†Luke Skywalker¬†to the Resistance. Disillusioned by the failures of the Jedi, Luke initially refuses, even after learning of¬†Han Solo's death. Unbeknownst to Luke, Rey and Kylo begin communicating with each other through telepathic visions. Prompted by R2-D2, Luke eventually agrees to teach Rey the ways of¬†the Force. Luke and Kylo give Rey differing accounts of the incident that turned Kylo to the dark side, with Luke confessing that he momentarily contemplated killing Kylo upon sensing that¬†Supreme Leader Snoke¬†had corrupted him, causing Kylo to destroy Luke's emergent Jedi Order in retaliation. Convinced that Kylo can still be redeemed, Rey leaves Ahch-To to confront Kylo without Luke. Luke prepares to burn down the Ahch-To Jedi temple and library, but he encounters¬†Yoda's Force ghost, who destroys the temple himself and encourages Luke to learn from his failure.

Holdo reveals her plan to discreetly evacuate the remaining Resistance members using small transports. Believing her actions to be cowardly and risky, Poe instigates a mutiny. Finn, Rose and BB-8 travel to Canto Bight and acquire the help of the hacker¬†DJ, who says he is able to help them disable the tracking device. They infiltrate Snoke's ship, but are captured by¬†Captain Phasma, though BB-8 manages to escape. Meanwhile, Rey lands on the ship, and Kylo brings her to Snoke, who reveals that he controlled the mental connection between her and Kylo as part of a plan to destroy Luke. Ordered to kill Rey, Kylo instead kills Snoke and works together with Rey to kill Snoke's guards. Kylo invites Rey to rule the galaxy with him, but Rey refuses. Using the Force, they struggle for possession of¬†Anakin Skywalker's lightsaber, which splits in two.

A recovered Leia stuns Poe, allowing the evacuation to begin. Holdo remains on the ship to mislead Snoke's fleet as all others attempt to flee to a nearby old¬†Rebel Alliancebase on¬†Crait. However, DJ reveals the Resistance's plan to the First Order, and the evacuation transports are targeted with heavy losses; Holdo sacrifices herself by ramming Snoke's fleet at lightspeed to stop the barrage. Rey escapes in the chaos, while Kylo declares himself new Supreme Leader. BB-8 frees Finn and Rose, who escape after defeating Captain Phasma, and join the survivors of the evacuation on Crait. When the First Order arrives, Poe, Finn, and Rose lead a charge with old¬†speeders. Rey draws the TIE fighters away with the¬†Falcon, while Rose saves Finn from a suicide run against the main enemy cannon, which blasts a hole in the Resistance fortress.

Luke appears and confronts Kylo alone so that the surviving Resistance fighters can escape. Kylo orders the First Order forces to fire on Luke to no effect, then engages Luke in battle himself. Kylo strikes Luke twice with his lightsaber, only to learn that he has been fighting Luke's Force¬†projection. Luke defiantly tells Kylo that he will not be the last Jedi, while Rey uses the Force to help the remaining Resistance fighters escape via the¬†Falcon. Back on Ahch-To, an exhausted Luke peacefully dies and becomes one with the Force. Leia reassures everyone that the rebellion has all that is needed to rise again. On Canto Bight, one of the children that helped Finn and Rose escape grabs a broom with the Force and gazes hopefully up into space.

Comment:
Now, I see the reasons for people hating this and reasons for people loving it.
-They are obviously going with the flow of women empowerment and I totally get why they would do that. I'm not in favor of this movement though because it's less about equality and more about being in charge of everything.
The Ocean's' movies are classic movies that have starred a diverse cast of men and women. To replace the whole cast with women feels like it's less about a fun movie and more about an agenda.

-The guys complaining about the movie aren't doing it because females. They're doing it because they are fans of the previous movies and they dislike the idea of swapping to an all female cast. They're not ALL misogynists.

-However, I do notice that a lot of the females in the comments are completely misandrist. Not all of them are, but it seems like if you post something negative, it's " man tears, hehhehe" or something of the sort. 

-Would you like it if Juno was remade with an all homosexual male cast? I don't think so.
-How about a Bridesmaids remake with an all male cast? Sound appetizing? I didn't think so.
-Kill Bill with a guy named Bill as the lead role? 
-I got it! Let's remake The Hunger Games with Brad Pitt as Katniss.
-Million Dollar Ben Affleck?

-This movie is not a good idea in my opinion and this "movement" is only dividing people.

-------This is coming from a FEMALE.

I love heist movies, but man oh man is this one gonna suck. Let me tell you why.
Ocean's Eleven: We are going to steal 160 mil in CASH from a casino's underground bank vault. Impressive.
Ocean's Twelve: We have to steal a a priceless Faberge egg from a museum while a another dick hole thief messes with us and actively trying to get us sent to jail and/or killed. Roundabout, but still impressive.
Ocean's Thirteen: We are going to rig an ENTIRE CASINO so literally everybody wins and you lose. And we are taking your diamonds. Petty and impressive.
Ocean's Eight: We are going to steal a necklace on a person... ARE YOU FUCKING SHITTING ME! You need 1 thief for that...maybe two. At least put the damn necklace in a high security bank vault or something.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
So a couple of thoughts...

1) Sandra Bullock plays a sibling of Danny Ocean, so technically it‚Äôs not a remake. It‚Äôs a spinoff taking place within the already existing ‚Äòocean‚Äôs universe‚Äô. Matt Damon is even appearing as his character from the original trilogy, undoubtedly to further establish connectivity between the franchises. 

2) The studio probably did a spinoff in order to avoid the ‚Äòfemale remake‚Äô label that would associate it with ghostbusters. However it‚Äôs the gender swap that makes people much more angry rather than seeing a remake, so they missed the mark there and surprise surprise the movie is getting hate right out of the gate, and will most likely bomb at the box office regardless of whether or not it is actually good. 

3) Though I value equality among men and women, I am not a fan of gender swapped movies. Let me emphasize ‚Äúgender swapped‚Äù. I have absolutely no problem with movies with female leads, there‚Äôs nothing wrong with that. I just find that gender swapping (in this case an originally all male movie) takes away from the message of ‚Äúempowerment‚Äù (or whatever message the filmmakers want) in exchange for making it Social Commentary: The Movie, and forcefully jamming it down the throats of the viewers. I believe that female led movies would receive much less hate if they were original stories and concepts  or adapted from other female centred works. And it doesn‚Äôt seem to go both ways. I‚Äôd imagine if a gender swapped movie that featured males instead of females were released it would also be torn apart and likely be called sexist. However I don‚Äôt believe in hating movies outright before its been viewed and its quality measured, though we absolutely have the right to be optimistic or doubtful.

4) I personally don‚Äôt think this movie will do well commercially. But it might do alright critically, seeing as ghostbusters got a certified fresh 74% on RT (even though it was terrible). If oceans 8 turns out to be bad i feel it will likely still get good reviews as critics will be afraid of suffering backlash from the public ( likely the case with ghostbusters)

5) despite my skepticism, I really do that hope this movie ends up being genuinely good, and a welcome addition to the oceans series. But again, I‚Äôm doubtful.

These are only my personal opinions, if you agree, cool, if not, that‚Äôs okay too. Let‚Äôs just hope this film turns out well.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
This movie doesn't look particularly appealing to me, and yes it because it stars an all-female cast. Well, sort of. I have no issues with all-female, or predominantly female casts. What I can't stand are movies that have so much political and ideological baggage. Like with Ghostbusters, even if the movie weren't terrible, I still had little chance of enjoying it because of all the nonsense leading up to it.

I really wish that people would let movies stand on their own merit. I don't care if you think this is an SJW takeover, or a feminist dream. When movies like this are held to some stupid standard because people want to adopt them as ammo to fit some personal ideology, for me it is a sure sign of failure.

Anyway, best of luck to this movie, but I'll be skipping it I suspect.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment: This movie is nothing more than a publicity stunt, plain and simple. Based on the trailer it seems like it could be a fun and interesting heist movie with several very talented actresses, so then why is it a part of the Ocean's franchise and not trying to do its own thing? Because like Ghostbusters and Star Wars, having a pre-established and popular title will already guarantee an audience that will pay money to go see it. As well as trying to create a controversy by casting all women with the sole intent of pushing an agenda and by shitting on its predecessor. Sparking the controversy is a pre-planned move to get the word out and hype up the movie. By doing this, it will get people who love it to see the movie as a way of supporting their beliefs, and it will get people who hate it to see the movie out of curiosity to find reasons for hating it. It's such a fucking shame that we're living in a time where the majority of films being produced are just rehashes made to push an agenda, and not to simply entertain an audience.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
It looks like a totally fine movie. However, there is always something strange about these women-remakes. It is not simply the fact, that women play lead roles as strong characters but that they do it in movies that had an original all-male cast and that it is done in a way that just screams "oh let's show them men". There seems to be not really another reason to remake an all-male ensemble film with an all-female cast, then to perpetuate this message. To underline this message you have the catchy tunes of "these boots are made for walkin" which is just one of the go-to songs whenever someone wants to showcase strong femininity. 

This is pretty bad for two reasons: first, you want these characters to be cool and tough but when the whole movie just becomes about "showing them men", the characters start to seem more needy and pathetic. Second, this just gives the impression that you don't know how to write interesting female characters without somehow referring to men.

Of course I don't know how the final movie will be. This is obviously just my impression from the trailer.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
It's funny how people complain about this being unoriginal but yet they praise the Clooney ones which not only were a remake but basically they made the same movie 3 times just by mixing it a bit, because the 3 with Clooney had the same basic concept with a similarly different frame. Get a grip, the message is not "Women can/should be able to do everything men do" or "We want to make a movie with only female actresses". Those may be parts of it and yes they benefit the Current feminist wave BUT these films are making you ACTIVELY think about inequality and gender issues simply by watching a trailer, something you wouldn't do with a movie that although has an original idea and interesting female roles is too subtle.
Some people prefer subtle and leading by example instead of the constant conversations about the same issues that are being held and posted all over. Personally, I am one of those but at the same time I can see reason in ways that are very obvious about what they're doing and saying as long as it's made in good faith. There are a lot of ways to get to one point and there isn't necessarily a right way, so think about everything form factually correct opinions with thoughtful arguments and challenge your own viewpoint, don't just judge away.
We live in an age in which we are being bombarded with these things from everywhere and we don't stop to think that if we didn't have our laptops and information didn't move as freely all around the world, we wouldn't have known about a film, a conversation or a protest for women's issues.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment: I can already hear the arguments concerning the similarities between this film and 2016's "Ghostbusters", but this time around, I think that Hollywood actually got the "gender swap" idea right.  In my opinion, "Ghostbusters: Answer the Call" was just too dumbed down and silly to be taken seriously, and as a result the suspense of disbelief constantly crumbled to pieces.  This film however, seems to have been made by a talented group of creators who actually took the concept and characters seriously, and as a result, it looks like a really good movie so far.  I'm very intrigued and want to see more, but before I commit to supporting this film in theaters, I'll need to see more trailers first.  I hope this film has a high level of quality throughout.  I guess only time will tell.  But for now, it earns a "thumbs up" from me.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment:
The problem with female versions of everything is that the female archetype/trope in film or any story telling is that there is always sex appeal--they're always another reincarnation of the Aphrodite. The appeal in the male Ocean's movies is that you had a wide range of archetypes, from dirty and lazy to tall and witty to old and wise to tiny and spunky. We don't have that here, we have one rehashed Aphrodite image after another. There will be panning make over fashion reveals, there will be cat-woman sex intimditation and there will be boredom. 

I'm a female and a writer and an artist, and I can't help but be dissatisfied at the thought that writers only have one archetype women in film. Where's the angry short grandma, the disastrously careless scientist with bad hair, the tall beautiful temptress with a lisp or stutter. It can't be all the perfect image. Ocean's charmed us all because everyone of his team members were misfits, and he loved them all loyally.  

A reused and recycled Kaling with her angsty Indian daughter role and another Bellatrix Lestrange don't cut it as creative story telling.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment: Alright, look. There's no way of knowing that this movie is going to be good or bad based on a single trailer. I mean, look at Jumanji. That was a sequel/reboot that looked terrible, but actually received pretty good reviews. The only reason people are disliking this is because of the female leads, and you can't try to blame it on "full of cliches" or "this person can't act." Some people are just extremely butthurt about movies with female leads. So what if they are trying to empower women? Women do make up a minority in this world, but are recently gaining more power through movements such as #metoo; and based on the comments below, they need it. "So they have to remake every classic film with female casts ..I blame dishwashers," and other sexist crap like that (that's a real comment, by the way, from JRM Productions). As for the movie itself, it isn't just a "carbon cashgrab copy" of Ocean's 11. The basic plot is similar, but the characters and setup is different enough to set it apart from its predecessors. In the end, we don't know if this movie is going to be good or bad, but we shouldn't be sexist jerks about it. The world has enough hate already.

Title: OCEAN'S 8 - Official 1st Trailer
Comment: I understand why some people might be upset at first, because from the outside at least it seems like nothing more than an exercise in Political Correctness, and it's been happening in lots of films/tv shows recently (e.g. Ghostbusters, Doctor Who, Planned Expandables All-Female Remake), but allow me to educate you - females exist. They aren't some out of left field minority, we're all actually birthed by females, and without them none of us could be here, so why are people surprised when they show up as the lead cast members in films. Also remakes themselves are nothing new (this is actually a spin-off but whatever), we should know by now that Hollywood has run out of ideas and maybe one of the only ways to keep things fresh is to change the gender of the cast. I also understand some peoples apprehensiveness that the movie will just suck, but this isn't by the same people that made Ghostbusters nor is it the same cast, I think with the right direction and cast this can be done right. Now I personally do not have any issue with them making an all-female remake in terms of the fact that I simply couldn't care less about the gender of the actors. I do think however that remakes like this can be more damaging for female equality than they are rewarding - why not make this movie but just call it something different, give it it's own voice? Either way some of the reasons people are bitching is rather silly because I can't see how casting females in something is trying to be politically correct. My final thought is this... maybe, JUST MAYBE, this movie will actually be good because it's well made and it's actually just enjoyable to watch... isn't that what we should merit films on?

The solution to not having enough strong female characters, is to give films a balanced cast that plays off of each character's strengths, rather than having one gender role defer to the other. You want to make another  Oceans film, then why not balance the cast with a few more strong female leads? Rather than going for the stock "wait I know, what if it was all women." 

Improving women's roles is more about giving them a staging ground amongst other strong male leads, rather than making all the males in the film weak, to try and bolster the perception of the women. It's called nuanced writing, and Hollywood seem to have forgotten how that works, or become too lazy to bother.

5/10, lukewarm but cautiously optimistic.
